                    h3.project-subheader May of 2023 to Present
                    a.project-link(aria-label="link to brianhayes.dev source code" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://github.com/tomit4/brianhayes.dev") Source Code/Documentation
                    h4.project-about About This Website
                    p.card.about-card "You're currently visiting my personal portfolio website and blog! Inspired in part by the minimalist style of <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to scribe" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://scribe.rip">Scribe</a>, this site is meant to invite you to take a look at some of my humble works and perhaps read one of my blog posts on software and other topics."
                    h4.project-about Project Description
                    p.card This blog is actually the third version of this website, which strives to be more readable and minimal than the previous two iterations. The last version of this blog, titled "LeafBytes", can still be found <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to leafbytes blog" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://leafbytes.com">here</a>, preserved for purposes of posterity. The previous version had some nice CSS animations (and a fun CyberPunk theme!). While, the <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to leafbytes repo" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://github.com/tomit4/leafbytes_vue">source code</a> features some of my essential skills in VueJS, in the end I had to admit that some of my design choices were not acceptable for a professional site/blog (unreadable small font sizes and distracting backgrounds). It wasn't long before I found myself wanting to get back to basics with this iteration of my blog. 
                    p.card Thusly, this latest version of my website is written in simple HTML, CSS, and a small amount of JavaScript (okay okay, I used <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to pugjs" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://pugjs.org/"> PugJS</a> instead of just pure HTML, but you get the idea &#128521;). It is running via an <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to nginx docs" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://nginx.org/">NGINX server</a> hosted on an <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to linode/akamai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://www.linode.com/">Akamai/Linode Cloud instance</a>. All these icons you see can be credited to the awesome designers over at <a class="inline-link" aria-label="link to iconify" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://iconify.design/"> Iconify!</a>
